The rigid physical pendulum is described in most introductory physics textbooks. When performing small amplitude oscillations in the absence of damping, such a pendulum has an oscillation period of

T=2π(Imglcm)1/2(1)(1)T=2π(Imglcm)1/2

where II is the moment of inertia of the pendulum with respect to the rotation axis, mm is the mass of the pendulum, gg is the gravitational acceleration, and lcmlcm is the distance from the axis of rotation of the pendulum to its center of mass.

The idealized geometry of a rigid three-bar pendulum is shown below.

A single, central bar of mass m1m1 and length l1l1 is assumed initially to rotate freely about an axis that is normal to the long axis of the bar. Two other bars, which are identical to each other and have mass m2m2 and length l2l2, are attached symmetrically to the central bar, with an overlap ss as shown.

When the long axis of the three-bar pendulum makes angle θθ measured counterclockwise with the downward vertical, the gravitational restoring torque acting on the pendulum relative to the rotation axis is −mglcmsinθ−mglcmsin⁡θ, where m≡m1+2m2m≡m1+2m2 is the total mass of the pendulum.

If we neglect any dissipative torques, then Newton’s Second Law for rotation is

Iθ¨=−mglcmsinθ(2)(2)Iθ¨=−mglcmsin⁡θ

We call this the equation of motion of the pendulum.

If, in addition, the amplitude of the oscillations is so small that θ<<1θ<<1 rad, then sinθsin⁡θ is accurately approximated by θθ and the equation is equivalent to that of a simple harmonic oscillator. This equation is a specific instance of the more general form

where the primes represent differentiation with respect to the independent variable uu. When q(u)q(u) and r(u)r(u) are such that an analytical solution is not possible, we need to numerically integrate the equation of motion to obtain approximate solutions.

Because computers work with pure numbers, it is advantageous to express the equation of motion in terms of dimensionless quantities (i.e., pure numbers). To do this, we need to intentionally choose a reasonable (constant) scaling factor, uscaleuscale, for the independent variable. For example, if the independent variable represents position, a length scale would be chosen; or if the independent variable represents time, a time scale would be chosen. The scaling factor uscaleuscale is then used to define the dimensionless variable u~≡u/uscaleu~≡u/uscale that will be used by the computer program to solve for the desired dependent variable yy. We have essentially done this above to obtain the dimensionless equation of motion. Specifically, we let t↔ut↔u, T↔uscaleT↔uscale, and t~≡t/T↔u~≡u/uscalet~≡t/T↔u~≡u/uscale.

One can carry out the same procedure with the more general equation to obtain the dimensionless form

We now describe the half-step approximation algorithm for solving this equation numerically if we are given the initial values of the dependent variable y(u~0)y(u~0) and its first derivative dy(u~0)/du~dy(u~0)/du~. To estimate the value of yywhen the independent dimensionless variable has the value u~=u~1=u~0+Δu~u~=u~1=u~0+Δu~, we choose to use the slope at the midpoint of the interval, given by

dy(u~1/2)du~(9)(9)dy(u~1/2)du~

where u~1/2=u~0+Δu~/2u~1/2=u~0+Δu~/2. We multiply this value of the slope by the interval Δu~Δu~ in order to get the change in the value of yy as we discuss below.

We obtain the value of this derivative from

dy(u~1/2)du~=dy(u~0)du~+d2y(u~0)du~2Δu~2(10)(10)dy(u~1/2)du~=dy(u~0)du~+d2y(u~0)du~2Δu~2

You can express the preceding equation in words as “the slope at the midpoint of the interval Δu~Δu~ is equal to the slope at the beginning of the interval plus the rate of change of the slope at the beginning of the interval multiplied by half the interval.” This will be perfectly accurate if the second derivative is a constant, and this provides one of the main motivations for using the half-step approximation. (Another motivation is that the error is bounded. See A. Cromer, “Stable solutions using the Euler approximation”, Am. J. Phys. 49 (5), 455-459 (1981)). If the second derivative is not constant, then this way of calculating the slope at the midpoint of the interval is only an approximation that becomes more accurate when using smaller intervals Δu~Δu~ of the independent dimensionless variable.

The slope at the midpoint of the interval, given above, can be used to take full steps of size Δu~Δu~ until the numerical solution has been propagated to the desired value of u~u~. The full steps are as follows. For the dependent variable, yy, we have

y(u~1)=y(u~0)+dy(u~1/2)du~Δu~(11)(11)y(u~1)=y(u~0)+dy(u~1/2)du~Δu~

For the second derivative of yy (recall that, for mechanics problems, this is essentially the recipe for the acceleration obtained by applying Newton’s Second Law), we have

d2y(u~1)du~2=−uscaleq(u~1)dy(u~1/2)du~−u2scaler(u~1)y(u~1)(12)(12)d2y(u~1)du~2=−uscaleq(u~1)dy(u~1/2)du~−uscale2r(u~1)y(u~1)

where u~3/2=u~0+3Δu~/2u~3/2=u~0+3Δu~/2.

For the first derivative of yy, we have

dy(u~3/2)du~=dy(u~1/2)du~+d2y(u~1)du~2(13)(13)dy(u~3/2)du~=dy(u~1/2)du~+d2y(u~1)du~2

It is worth noting that in the equation for d2y(u~1)/du~2d2y(u~1)/du~2 we are assuming that

dy(u~1/2)du~≈dy(u~1)du~(14)(14)dy(u~1/2)du~≈dy(u~1)du~

In other words, the differential equation requires that all functions and derivatives be evaluated at the same point (i.e., the same value of the independent variable); but we are explicitly NOT doing so. Therefore, the usefulness of the method depends on the accuracy of this approximation. A crude, but practical, test of the convergence of the numerical solution is to halve the step size Δu~Δu~ and compare the new solution to the prior solution. If there is no signifcant difference within the numerical accuracy desired, then the step size is adequate.
